    <h3>2. Getting Started</h3>
    <p>
        Before getting started, we should know the value, worth of the project we're making. It's not just a minor project, just like other compiler apps, <b>(Like the Spck Editor, Trebedit or any other copiler app not mentioned)</b>. This is a premium app with about 6 apps embedded in. We should take the app professional, no unnecessary features, unprofessional designs, or any simulated features(Unless it's the SQL table Simulation with local storage)
    </p>

    <h4>a. Downloading all the needed Libraries.</h4>
    <p>
        Making our own libraries is the best option, if we were a big team of about 100, it can take about a year if we make everything our own. For that case, we shall use existing libraries to ease the functionality, and focus on the app logic. 
        They may include;
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Tailwind CSS - for all the app pages design</li>
        <li>Ace Editor - for all the code editors.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>b. The app structure.</h4>
    <p>The app will use Webview, 70% since we cannot implement all those features so easily. Only the making of the interactions may take 200Mbs, and the Java Logic isn't so easy to make without errors, yet JavaScript can do it easier if granted access. We can create the bridge with Java, then JavaScript does the most.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>The Webview - all pages</li>
        <li>Inbuilt Browser - Another Webview</li>
        <li>The Terminal Layout - Fully Made with XML and C++</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3. Conclusion</h3>
    <p>If you're among the B-IDE team, you're requested to take responsibility and participate in the project, choose your role, play it.</p>
    
